`3.0.1` is not a number, it is basically a sequence of numbers separated by periods.

One idea is to make a class which represents this version number. We interpret a version code like `3.0.1` as a sequence of numbers separated by periods; basically an array with `int`s. We can just split the input string by the period character, resulting in components of the version number. In a version number, each integer can be called a &#39;component&#39;. The version number `3.0.1` has three components: `3`, `0` and `1`.

Once we have created two `Version` instances, we can compare them with eachother. The comparison is as follows: for each component the `Version` instance has, that component will be matched against the component at the same position in another version.

    public class Version implements Comparable&lt;Version&gt; {

        private List&lt;Integer&gt; components = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();
        
        public Version(String version) {
            String[] parts = version.split(&quot;\\.&quot;);
            for (String part : parts) {
                // Parse the integer. We assume it is a valid number
                this.components.add(Integer.parseInt(part));
            }
        }

        @Override
        public int compareTo(Version o) {
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; this.components.size(); i++) {
                // Compare the corresponding elements with eachother.
                // We assume the lengths of the &#39;numbers&#39; are equal.
                int compare = this.components.get(i).compareTo(o.components.get(i));
                if (compare != 0) {
                    return compare;
                }
            }
            return 0;
        }
    }

